  <body>
    <sec sec-type="Introduction">
      <title>Introduction</title>
      <p><italic><tp:taxon-name><tp:taxon-name-part taxon-name-part-type="genus">Orphnus</tp:taxon-name-part></tp:taxon-name></italic> Macleay, 1819, is the most speciose genus of the scarab beetle subfamily <tp:taxon-name><tp:taxon-name-part taxon-name-part-type="subfamily">Orphninae</tp:taxon-name-part></tp:taxon-name> comprising currently about 100 nominal species (<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B1602278">Paulian 1948</xref>, <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B1602288">Petrovitz 1971</xref>). Most of the <italic><tp:taxon-name><tp:taxon-name-part taxon-name-part-type="genus">Orphnus</tp:taxon-name-part></tp:taxon-name></italic> species have a more or less developed head and pronotal armature. One of the two species with a strongly bifurcated clypeal horn, <italic><tp:taxon-name><tp:taxon-name-part taxon-name-part-type="genus">O.</tp:taxon-name-part> <tp:taxon-name-part taxon-name-part-type="species">drumonti</tp:taxon-name-part></tp:taxon-name></italic> Frolov, 2009, has so far been known from a single type specimen (<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B1601932">Frolov 2009</xref>).</p>
      <p><italic><tp:taxon-name><tp:taxon-name-part taxon-name-part-type="genus">Delopleurus</tp:taxon-name-part></tp:taxon-name></italic> Erichson, 1847, comprises 10 superficially similar, small-sized species distributed in the Afrotropical region and Southern Asia (<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B1602008">Frolov 2014</xref>, <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B1602248">Král 2014</xref>). The genus is commonly classed as dung beetles, however, there is no evidence of its association with dung but rather with higher fungi. Most of the <italic><tp:taxon-name><tp:taxon-name-part taxon-name-part-type="genus">Delopleurus</tp:taxon-name-part></tp:taxon-name></italic> species occur in the Afrotropical Region and a few of them are known only from the type material. Of them <italic><tp:taxon-name><tp:taxon-name-part taxon-name-part-type="genus">Delopleurus</tp:taxon-name-part> <tp:taxon-name-part taxon-name-part-type="species">naviauxi</tp:taxon-name-part></tp:taxon-name></italic> Frolov et Cambefort in Frolov, 2014, was described from two females and no more material was available until recently.</p>
      <p>Examination of the collections of the museums listed below revealed additional material which provided new locality records of the two species and allowed descriptions of the sexes lacked in the type series.</p>
    </sec>
    <sec sec-type="materials|methods">
      <title>Materials and methods</title>
      <p>Examined material is housed in the National Museum of Natural History “Naturalis”, Leiden (RMNH) and Zoological Museum of University of Copenhagen, Copenhagen (ZMUC).</p>
      <p>Preparation of genitalia follows the common technique used in entomological research. Partially focused serial images were combined in Helicon Focus software (Helicon Soft Ltd.) to produce completely focused images. The photographs were not altered except for levels and tone correction in Adobe Photoshop. The distribution map was generated with ArcGIS software. Co-ordinates of the localities were taken from the specimens labels, if available, or from the NGA GEOnet Names Server (GNS, <ext-link ext-link-type="uri" xlink:href="http://geonames.nga.mil/gns/html/">geonames.nga.mil/gns/html/</ext-link>). Ecoregion names follow <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B1602108">Olson et al. (2001)</xref>.</p>
    </sec>
